@startuml DigitalWellbeing_InterviewFlow

skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam rectangleBorderColor #555555
skinparam rectangleRoundCorner 15
skinparam arrowColor #444444
skinparam arrowThickness 2

title <size:22>Digital Wellbeing System — Bottom-Up Interview Walkthrough</size>\n<size:13>Start from Step 1. Each step answers the natural next question.</size>


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 1: What are we even tracking?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 1: What are we tracking?**" as S1 #E8F5E9 {
    rectangle "  **AppInfo**\n  packageName : String\n  displayName : String\n  category : AppCategory  " as S1a #White
    rectangle "  **AppCategory** (enum)\n  SOCIAL_MEDIA | PRODUCTIVITY\n  ENTERTAINMENT | GAMING  " as S1b #White
    S1a -right-> S1b : has >
}

note right of S1 #C8E6C9
    **SAY:** "Let's start simple. We're tracking
    apps. Each app has a package name
    (com.instagram), a display name,
    and a category."

    No patterns yet. Just data.
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 2: What does "usage" look like?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 2: What does one usage session look like?**" as S2 #E8F5E9 {
    rectangle "  **UsageSession**\n  app : AppInfo\n  startTime : long\n  endTime : long\n  + getDurationMillis() : long\n  + isActive() : boolean  " as S2a #White
    rectangle "  **DailyUsageSummary**\n  date : LocalDate\n  app : AppInfo\n  totalTimeMillis : long\n  sessionCount : int\n  + getTotalMinutes() : int  " as S2b #White
    S2b o-left- S2a : aggregates
}

note right of S2 #C8E6C9
    **SAY:** "When you open Instagram at 10am
    and close at 10:30am, that's one
    **UsageSession** (30 min duration).

    All sessions of one app on one day
    get rolled up into a **DailyUsageSummary**.

    These are just data holders. **(SRP)**"
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 3: Who creates these sessions?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 3: Who creates and manages sessions?**" as S3 #E3F2FD {
    rectangle "  **ScreenTimeTracker** <<Singleton>>\n  ──────────────────────────────────\n  - activeSessions : Map\n  - observers : List\n  ──────────────────────────────────\n  + getInstance() : ScreenTimeTracker\n  + onAppOpened(app) -> creates UsageSession\n  + onAppClosed(app) -> ends session, fires event  " as S3a #White
}

note right of S3 #BBDEFB
    **SAY:** "We need something that listens for
    app open/close and creates sessions.
    That's the **ScreenTimeTracker**.

    **Why Singleton?** If we have 2 tracker
    instances, sessions get double-counted.
    One device = one tracker = one source
    of truth."

    **Pattern: Singleton**
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 4: When a session ends, lots of things need to happen...
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 4: App closed — now what? Multiple things must happen!**" as S4 #FFF3E0 {
    rectangle "  <<interface>>\n  **UsageEventObserver**\n  + onUsageEvent(event)  " as S4i #White
    rectangle "  **PersistenceObserver**\n  -> save session to disk  " as S4a #White
    rectangle "  **StatisticsUpdateObserver**\n  -> refresh the stats UI  " as S4b #White
    rectangle "  **UsageLimitObserver**\n  -> check if daily limit hit  " as S4c #White
    S4i -down-> S4a
    S4i -down-> S4b
    S4i -down-> S4c
}

note right of S4 #FFE0B2
    **SAY:** "When a session ends, 3 things
    must happen: save data, update UI,
    check limits. But the tracker shouldn't
    know about any of that.

    **Problem:** tight coupling if tracker
    directly calls persistence, stats, limits.

    **Solution: Observer Pattern.**
    Tracker just says 'something happened'.
    Each observer reacts independently.

    **Want to add SMS alerts later?**
    Add one observer. Tracker unchanged. **(OCP)**"

    **Pattern: Observer**
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 5: Where does the data actually get saved?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 5: Where does data get stored? (survives reboots)**" as S5 #FFEBEE {
    rectangle "  <<interface>> **UsageRepository**\n  + saveSession(session)\n  + getDailySummary(app, date)\n  + deleteOlderThan(date)  " as S5r #White
    rectangle "  <<interface>> **PersistenceStrategy**\n  + write(key, data)\n  + read(key)\n  + delete(key)  " as S5s #White
    rectangle "  **SQLitePersistence**  " as S5a #White
    rectangle "  **FilePersistence**  " as S5b #White
    rectangle "  **SharedPrefsPersistence**  " as S5c #White
    S5r -down-> S5s : delegates to
    S5s -down-> S5a
    S5s -down-> S5b
    S5s -down-> S5c
}

note right of S5 #FFCDD2
    **SAY:** "The PersistenceObserver needs
    to save data somewhere durable
    (must survive reboots).

    **Problem:** If we hardcode SQLite
    everywhere, we can't swap to file
    storage for tests.

    **Solution: Two patterns together.**

    **Repository Pattern** — business logic
    calls saveSession(). Doesn't know
    if it's SQLite, file, or cloud. **(DIP)**

    **Strategy Pattern** — actual storage
    is pluggable. SQLite for prod,
    InMemory for unit tests. **(OCP, LSP)**"

    **Patterns: Repository + Strategy**
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 6: How do we show usage stats to the user?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 6: How do we display usage statistics?**" as S6 #F3E5F5 {
    rectangle "  **UsageStatisticsService**\n  + getWeeklyReport() : UsageReport\n  + getMostUsedApps(days) : List  " as S6a #White
    rectangle "  **UsageReportBuilder** <<Builder>>\n  + setDateRange(start, end)\n  + addDailySummary(s)\n  + build() : UsageReport  " as S6b #White
    rectangle "  **UsageReport** (immutable)\n  totalHours, dailyAverage\n  appBreakdown  " as S6c #White
    S6a -right-> S6b : uses >
    S6b -right-> S6c : builds >
}

note right of S6 #E1BEE7
    **SAY:** "The stats service reads from
    the repository and builds a report.

    **Problem:** UsageReport has 5+ fields.
    Constructor with 6 params is unreadable.

    **Solution: Builder Pattern.**
    builder.setDateRange(mon, sun)
      .addDailySummary(mon)
      .addDailySummary(tue)
      .build()

    Clean, readable, validated. **(SRP)**"

    **Pattern: Builder**
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 7: How do we keep only 7 days?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 7: How do we enforce the 7-day window?**" as S7 #E0F7FA {
    rectangle "  **DataRetentionManager**\n  retentionDays = 7\n  + purgeExpiredData()\n  calls repo.deleteOlderThan(today - 7)  " as S7a #White
}

note right of S7 #B2EBF2
    **SAY:** "Simple. On every app startup,
    this manager calls deleteOlderThan().
    Storage stays bounded.

    Change to 30 days? One field. **(SRP)**"
end note


' ====================================================================
'  STEP 8: How does it all come together?
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**STEP 8: Tie it all together — the Facade**" as S8 #E8EAF6 {
    rectangle "  **DigitalWellbeingSystem** <<Facade>>\n  ──────────────────────────────────\n  + initialize()   -> wires everything up\n  + onAppOpened()  -> delegates to tracker\n  + onAppClosed()  -> delegates to tracker\n  + getUsageStats() -> delegates to stats service\n  + setDailyLimit() -> delegates to limit observer  " as S8a #White
}

note right of S8 #BBDEFB
    **SAY:** "Finally, the client shouldn't know
    about trackers, observers, repositories.
    **Facade Pattern** — one class, one API.
    Client calls onAppOpened(). Done.
    All the wiring is hidden inside."

    **Pattern: Facade**
end note


' ====================================================================
'  FLOW ARROWS — each asks the natural next question
' ====================================================================
S1 -down-> S2 : "  OK, but what does a usage record look like?  "
S2 -down-> S3 : "  Who creates these sessions?  "
S3 -down-> S4 : "  Session ended. Now what?  "
S4 -down-> S5 : "  Observer saves data... but where?  "
S5 -down-> S6 : "  Data is stored. How do we show it?  "
S6 -down-> S7 : "  Stats work. How to keep only 7 days?  "
S7 -down-> S8 : "  Everything works. How to expose it cleanly?  "


' ====================================================================
'  CLOSING
' ====================================================================
rectangle "**WRAP UP — Say This**" as CLOSE #F5F5F5 {
    rectangle "  \"We started with concrete models, built tracking on top,\n  used Observer to decouple reactions, Repository + Strategy\n  for durable + swappable persistence, Builder for clean reports,\n  and Facade to hide it all behind one API.\n\n  6 patterns, each solving a specific problem.\n  All 3 requirements met.\"  " as CLOSE_text #FFFDE7
}

S8 -down-> CLOSE


' ====================================================================
'  REQUIREMENTS MAP
' ====================================================================
legend bottom
    |= Requirement |= Steps That Solve It |
    | Track screen time of different apps | Steps 1-4 (Models + Tracker + Observers) |
    | Display usage statistics | Step 6 (StatsService + Builder) |
    | Persist data for 7 days across reboots | Step 5 (Repository + Strategy) + Step 7 (Retention) |
endlegend

@enduml
